rummy 2025-06-28 12:21 p.m.
Well to start with since you brought up an issue that not enough information on the prosecutors conduct was established. As you know, we were going to file for sanctions. On that document, we held arguments that the Court's recent opinion did not address, specifically:
rummy 2025-06-28 12:22 p.m.
The Prosecutor Knowingly Made False Statements to the Court. In our original draft for sanctions, we argue dthat the Prosecutor, PotatoGamble, lied on the official court record. He claimed the State was withdrawing from the deposition agreement because a "good faith + cooperation contract" was broken. However, his own written communications show the actual reason was retaliation for the Defendant exercising his right to pursue a separate, lawful litigation hold. This was a deliberate falsehood designed to hide his improper retaliatory motive. The Prosecutor Engaged in Impermissible Retaliatory Prosecution. Our motion establishes a textbook example of retaliatory prosecution. The prosecutor's own message directly links his punitive actions, canceling the deposition and the plea deal, to the Defendant's protected legal activity. He explicitly stated, "...it appears your defense team is attempting to sue half the department of justice. Not the greatest show of cooperation. this deposition is over and no plea deal will be made". This is direct evidence of his retaliatory animus.
rummy 2025-06-28 12:22 p.m.
You cite Goodwin. First, Goodwin addresses the presumption of prosecutorial vindictiveness in the context of pretrial plea negotiations and charging decisions, holding that such a presumption does not generally arise when a prosecutor increases charges after a defendant exercises a legal right before trial. The Supreme Court explained, “a change in the charging decision made after an initial trial is completed is much more likely to be improperly motivated than is a pretrial decision” and that “in the pretrial context, the opportunity for vindictiveness is much less, and a change in the charging decision in response to a defendant’s plea negotiation posture is an accepted part of the process”. However, the conduct alleged in the motion for sanctions draft is not a routine pretrial charging or plea negotiation adjustment. Instead, the motion alleges that the prosecutor made knowingly false statements to the court, explicitly retaliated against the defendant for exercising a protected right (serving a litigation hold), and used threats and coercion unrelated to the merits of the case. These are not the types of discretionary, pretrial decisions that Goodwin protects from a presumption of vindictiveness. Rather, they are direct, documented acts of retaliation and dishonesty, which courts have recognized as outside the scope of Goodwin’s holding.
rummy 2025-06-28 12:23 p.m.
As you see, for this first part reconsideration would be appropriate since it would allow us to bring those elements to your attention, that weren't on the State's motion to dismiss
rummy 2025-06-28 12:25 p.m.
Also I have some points I want to bring up on the case law you cited regarding limiting the State's authority on prosecutorial discretion, specifically mention of the “leave of court” requirement, which is designed primarily to protect against prosecutorial harassment, such as repeated charging and dismissing to harass a defendant, not to allow courts to second-guess the executive’s charging decisions. The overwhelming weight of authority holds that, absent prosecutorial bad faith or a motion “clearly contrary to manifest public interest,” the court must grant the government’s motion to dismiss.

PAPERLESS ORDER TO SHOW CAUSE

In the case of State of Mayflower v. Deletevictim (2025), prosecutor for the Department of Justice PotatoGamble knowingly made false statements within the presence of the court to the defendant's counsel on or about June 27th. Defense counsel has presented clear and damning evidence demonstrating contemnor's misconduct during negotiations for a deposition with the defendant's counsel. The contemnor has also engaged in a pattern of conduct which demonstrates a severe lack of respect for ethical obligations as a bar-certified attorney, going so far as to utter threats of moving forwards with the "death penalty," and utilizing deception tactics in order to intimidate and force the defendant to comply with the State's deposition. When defendant's counsel exercised their right to issue a written notice to the Justice Department to preserve evidence, the contemnor ceased all attempts at negotiating with defense counsel due "[defense counsel] attempting to sue half the department of justice."*Def. Motion for Sanctions *Exhibit B.

Based on this pattern of behavior, the contemnor has breached his duties and obligations as a State prosecutor. This Court holds zero tolerance for prosecutors attempting to intimidate, coerce, and retaliate against defendants for not falling in line with their directives.
Singhski ᴘᴄ 2025-06-28 04:48 p.m.
As a result of his actions, the contemnor shall be required to attend a hearing in order to show cause as to why he should not be held in contempt pursuant to 5 M.S.C 1 § 2104.1 which permits sanctions for: "misbehavior in the presence of the court or near thereto obstructing the administration of justice", "misbehavior by an officer of the court in officials transactions" and "disobedience to a lawful...command".

The contemnor is informed that not giving a sufficient explanation for their actions will lead to the application of penalties without them being able to contest or provide any explanation. These sanctions may include jail time, a fine and referral to the Mayflower State Bar.

SO ORDERED, this Saturday, 28th of June, 2025.
